diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE is a chronic autoimmune disease that can affect various organs and tissues of the body, causing widespread inflammation. Symptoms such as synovitis, pleural effusion, acute pericarditis, seizure, and proteinuria are common in SLE patients.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: While primarily affecting the joints, rheumatoid arthritis can also manifest extra-articular features including pleural effusion and rarely, pericarditis. Synovitis is a hallmark of the disease.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Sclerosis (Scleroderma)
diagnoses.rationale: This is an autoimmune disorder characterized by changes in the skin, blood vessels, muscles, and internal organs. Pleural effusion, acute pericarditis, and proteinuria can be manifestations of systemic sclerosis.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.rationale: MCTD features signs and symptoms of a combination of disorders — lupus, scleroderma, and polymyositis. Patients may present with synovitis, pleural effusion, pericarditis, and proteinuria.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Primarily affecting salivary and lacrimal glands, it can also cause extraglandular manifestations including arthritis (synovitis) and involvement of the renal system (proteinuria).

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout the body, which can lead to numerous symptoms including those affecting the joints (synovitis), and potentially, neurological complications (seizures).

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.rationale: This represents a group of disorders that destroy blood vessels by inflammation. It can lead to symptoms like pericarditis and proteinuria depending on the type of vasculitis and the organs affected.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis (extrapulmonary)
diagnoses.rationale: Extrapulmonary TB can manifest in various forms including pleurisy with effusion, pericarditis, and can affect the kidneys, leading to proteinuria. Joint involvement might mimic synovitis.

diagnoses.name: Viral Infections
diagnoses.rationale: Certain viral infections can cause a complex set of symptoms including pericarditis, seizures, and proteinuria, depending on the virus and the body systems it affects.

diagnoses.name: Post-Streptococcal Glomerulonephritis
diagnoses.rationale: Following a strep throat infection, this condition can cause proteinuria and occasionally, other systemic symptoms due to the body's immune response to the infection.

diagnoses.name: Viral Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the brain caused by a virus; can lead to seizures, delirium, and rashes in severe cases.

diagnoses.name: Erythema Infectiosum (Fifth Disease)
diagnoses.description: A viral infection that often causes a maculopapular rash, and in rare cases, can cause complications leading to pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can cause a wide range of symptoms including seizures, rashes, and pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Dengue Fever
diagnoses.description: A mosquito-borne virus that can cause severe flu-like symptoms, rash, and in serious cases, lead to significant complications like pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever
diagnoses.description: A tick-borne illness that typically presents with a maculopapular rash, and can also lead to severe complications including delirium and seizures.

diagnoses.name: Toxic Shock Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, life-threatening complication of certain bacterial infections, associated with rash, seizures, and multi-organ involvement including pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Meningococcemia
diagnoses.description: A bacterial infection that can lead to widespread blood infection, causing petechial rash, seizures, and in severe cases, delirium.

diagnoses.name: Acute Rheumatic Fever
diagnoses.description: A disease that can occur following a 'Streptococcus pyogenes' infection, causing a variety of symptoms including rash, seizures, and pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki Disease
diagnoses.description: An illness that mainly affects children under 5 years old, causing fever, rash, and could lead to complications like pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: Caused by the 'Borrelia burgdorferi' bacteria transmitted through tick bites. It can present with neurological manifestations such as seizures and a characteristic rash.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.reason: SLE can manifest with a wide range of symptoms including acute pericarditis, nephritis, arthropathy, and skin manifestations such as maculopapular rash. Follicular hyperkeratosis is less common but can be present.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.reason: Rheumatoid arthritis primarily affects joints causing arthropathy but can also have systemic manifestations including pericarditis and skin rashes.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.reason: Dermatomyositis is characterized by muscle weakness and distinctive skin rashes, which may include maculopapular rashes. It can also sometimes result in pericarditis.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.reason: This disease exhibits features of several connective tissue diseases including SLE, polymyositis, and scleroderma. Symptoms can include pericarditis, nephritis, arthropathy, and skin rashes.

diagnoses.name: Psoriatic Arthritis
diagnoses.reason: Psoriatic arthritis can cause arthropathy, and it is associated with skin lesions. While pericarditis and nephritis are less common, they can occur in severe cases.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.reason: Sarcoidosis can affect any organ in the body, including the skin (leading to various rashes), joints (causing arthropathy), and heart (causing pericarditis). Kidney involvement is less common but possible.

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki Disease
diagnoses.reason: Kawasaki disease primarily affects children and can result in a maculopapular rash, arthropathy, and heart complications including pericarditis, though nephritis is rare.

diagnoses.name: Adult-onset Still's Disease
diagnoses.reason: This inflammatory disease can cause a characteristic salmon-pink rash, fever, arthralgia, and pericarditis. Renal involvement is less common.

diagnoses.name: Henoch-Schönlein Purpura
diagnoses.reason: This vasculitis can cause a characteristic purpuric rash, arthralgia, abdominal pain, and can affect the kidneys (nephritis). Pericarditis is rare.

diagnoses.name: Viral Infections
diagnoses.reason: Certain viral infections can cause a cluster of these symptoms, including a maculopapular rash, arthropathy, and acute pericarditis. Direct kidney damage (nephritis) can occur but is more atypical.

diagnoses.name: Endometriosis
diagnoses.description: A painful, chronic condition where tissue similar to the lining inside the uterus grows outside the uterus.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.description: A common type of anemia that occurs due to insufficient dietary intake and absorption of iron, or iron loss from bleeding which can occur from a variety of sources, including heavy menstrual periods often associated with endometriosis.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A group of diseases that result in high blood sugar (hyperglycemia) over a prolonged period. It can lead to joint pain and is associated with a wide range of complications.

diagnoses.name: Osteoarthritis
diagnoses.description: A degenerative joint disease causing joint pain and stiffness. It could be associated with obesity, which is a common factor in poorly controlled diabetes.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that causes chronic inflammation of joints, leading to pain and possibly in association with autoimmune conditions related to endometriosis.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition involving the gradual loss of kidney function. It can lead to anemia and hyperglycemia if diabetes is poorly controlled.

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by hormonal imbalance and metabolism problems, which can lead to hyperglycemia. It’s also associated with chronic inflammation, which can exacerbate joint pain.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory and mood issues. It can be associated with symptoms like joint pain.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease in which the immune system attacks its own tissues, causing widespread inflammation and tissue damage in the affected organs, including joints.

diagnoses.name: Thyroid Disorders
diagnoses.description: Disorders that affect the thyroid gland. Hypothyroidism, for example, can lead to symptoms such as joint pain, fatigue, and can be associated with menstrual irregularities.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD)
diagnoses.rationale: Wheezing is a common symptom along with the potential for secondary polycythemia due to chronic hypoxia.

diagnoses.name: Asthma
diagnoses.rationale: Wheezing is a primary symptom. Secondary conditions or symptomatology could contribute to or exacerbate other listed symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Obstructive Sleep Apnea
diagnoses.rationale: Can lead to secondary polycythemia due to chronic hypoxia. Symptoms like irritability and hyperactivity might be present due to disrupted sleep patterns.

diagnoses.name: Bronchitis
diagnoses.rationale: Chronic bronchitis can cause wheezing and may be associated with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, which could lead to symptoms like polycythemia.

diagnoses.name: Heart Failure
diagnoses.rationale: Might cause wheezing similar to cardiac asthma. The condition could contribute to secondary polycythemia via chronic hypoxia.

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.rationale: This is a primary blood disorder that leads to an increased number of red blood cells (polycythemia). Symptoms might indirectly influence or be perceived as irritability or hyperactivity.

diagnoses.name: Pulmonary Embolism
diagnoses.rationale: Can cause wheezing and secondary polycythemia due to hypoxemia. Could also lead to irritability and hyperactivity due to the body's stress response.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.rationale: While primarily affecting the digestive system, GERD can cause wheezing and respiratory symptoms due to aspiration. Connection to other symptoms is less direct.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.rationale: Can manifest physically as hyperactivity and irritability, with stress potentially exacerbating asthma or COPD, leading to wheezing.

diagnoses.name: Periodontal Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Listed as a symptom, but its presence can exacerbate or signal systemic inflammation or other conditions, indirectly affecting systemic health and possibly contributing to conditions like polycythemia due to chronic inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Reaction
diagnoses.reasoning: Symptoms such as oral pain, angioedema, and migratory patchy macular erythema go along with an allergic reaction. Post-nasal drip may also present due to nasal congestion related to allergies.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: Characterized by oral pain due to dry mouth, can also lead to decreased libido as a result of overall discomfort and systemic effects. However, it does not typically cause angioedema or migratory erythema.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: It can present with oral pain (mouth sores), and although less common, it might cause skin manifestations similar to migratory patchy macular erythema. Decreased libido could be associated with the chronic nature of the condition.

diagnoses.name: Drug Reaction
diagnoses.reasoning: Some medications can cause oral pain, angioedema, and skin reactions such as migratory patchy macular erythema. A side effect of medications can also include decreased libido.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson Syndrome/Toxic Epidermal Necrolysis
diagnoses.reasoning: This severe reaction could explain oral pain, skin eruptions, and angioedema. It is an emergency medical condition.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Mononucleosis
diagnoses.reasoning: Often presents with a sore throat (which could present as oral pain), general malaise, and possibly a maculopapular rash. Post-nasal drip may also be present. Decreased libido could stem from the generalized illness.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Progesterone Dermatitis
diagnoses.reasoning: Features might include migratory patchy macular erythema related to menstrual cycle changes, which may be associated with systemic symptoms such as angioedema. The condition could indirectly affect libido due to discomfort.

diagnoses.name: Eosinophilic Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis
diagnoses.reasoning: May cause oral pain and could potentially lead to symptoms such as migratory patchy macular erythema. This rare condition might also explain post-nasal drip due to sinus inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.reasoning: Characterized primarily by angioedema but can be accompanied by transient rashes similar to macular erythema. Oral pain may arise from swelling. Not directly associated with decreased libido.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.reasoning: Can present with decreased libido and, less commonly, skin changes. Though not typically associated with oral pain or angioedema, it can have wide-reaching systemic effects, including fatigue that might exacerbate other symptoms.

diagnoses: Gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) with eosinophilic esophagitis

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: Fibromyalgia is a disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory and mood issues. It may lead to symptoms like chronic back pain and difficulty concentrating.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Chronic fatigue syndrome is a complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that cannot be explained by any underlying medical condition. The fatigue can worsen with physical or mental activity but doesn't improve with rest.

diagnoses.name: Lupus (Systemic Lupus Erythematosus)
diagnoses.description: Lupus is an autoimmune disease that occurs when your body's immune system attacks your own tissues and organs, potentially causing symptoms like migratory edema, ulcers, and vulvodynia.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: Rheumatoid arthritis is a chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including those in the hands and feet. The condition can cause a range of symptoms, including chronic pain.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: Multiple sclerosis is a disease of the central nervous system in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. It can manifest with symptoms such as difficulty concentrating and chronic pain.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Sjögren's syndrome is a disorder of your immune system identified by its two most common symptoms — dry eyes and a dry mouth. It may also lead to systemic symptoms including chronic pain and fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: Vasculitis involves inflammation of the blood vessels, which can cause the walls of the vessels to thicken, reducing the width of the passageway through the vessel. It may lead to a variety of symptoms, including ulcers and edema.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: Lyme disease is transmitted to humans through the bite of infected black-legged ticks. Symptoms can include fatigue, headache, muscle and joint aches, and cognitive defects, such as difficulty concentrating.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Venous Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: Chronic venous insufficiency occurs when the venous wall and/or valves in the leg veins are not working effectively, making it difficult for blood to return to the heart from the legs. This condition can cause ulcers and edema.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.description: Behçet's disease is a rare disorder that causes blood vessel inflammation throughout your body. The disease can lead to numerous signs and symptoms that may seem unrelated at first, including ulcers and chronic pain.

diagnoses.name: Hemochromatosis
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder causing the body to absorb too much iron from the diet. The excess iron is stored in various organs, particularly the liver, causing symptoms like abnormal liver enzymes, and it can also affect the spleen leading to anemia or leukopenia.

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.description: A type of blood cancer that causes the bone marrow to make too many red blood cells. This can lead to thickened blood and increased risk of clots. It might also involve lymph node enlargement and can indirectly affect liver function.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Lymphoproliferative Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An immune system disorder where the body can't properly regulate the number of immune cells. This leads to lymphadenopathy, and can also cause anemia, leukopenia, and liver enzyme abnormalities.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A cancer of the lymphatic system. It can cause lymphadenitis, abnormalities in blood cell counts including leukopenia and polycythemia in rare cases, and liver enzyme abnormalities due to liver involvement.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human Immunodeficiency Virus compromises the immune system by destroying CD4 T cells, leading to lymphadenopathy, leukopenia due to the immune response, and can also affect the liver's functionality.

diagnoses.name: Hepatitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the liver, which may be caused by viral infections, toxins, alcohol, or autoimmune diseases. It can manifest with cyst formation in the liver, abnormal liver enzymes, and can sometimes cause issues with blood cell counts.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease affecting multiple organs, particularly the lungs and lymph glands. It can cause granulomas to form in these organs, leading to lymphadenitis, abnormal liver enzymes, and it might affect blood cell production leading to leukopenia.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis. While primarily affecting the lungs, it can spread and cause lymphadenitis, impact the liver's functionality, and cause a range of hematological abnormalities.

diagnoses.name: Gaucher's Disease
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder in which fatty substances accumulate in cells and certain organs. This can lead to liver enlargement and dysfunction (abnormal liver enzymes), thrombocytopenia, and anemia, which may mimic leukopenia.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Myeloid Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that starts in the blood-forming cells of the bone marrow and invades the blood. It can cause elevated white blood cell counts initially but may lead to leukopenia due to treatment or disease progression. It can also cause spleen enlargement and liver enzymes abnormalities.

diagnoses: Autoimmune diseases (e.g., systemic lupus erythematosus, rheumatoid arthritis)
Inflammatory bowel disease (e.g., Crohn's disease, ulcerative colitis)

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: Fibromyalgia is a disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory and mood issues. It may go along with symptoms like muscle pain and can indirectly relate to word-finding difficulties due to cognitive impairments known as 'fibro fog'.

diagnoses.name: Systemic lupus erythematosus
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease where the body's immune system mistakenly attacks healthy tissue. It can cause widespread inflammation and tissue damage in the affected organs, including skin (Dermatographism), muscles (pain), and the brain (word-finding difficulty, headache).

diagnoses.name: Thyroid disorders
diagnoses.description: Hyperthyroidism or hypothyroidism can manifest with muscle pain, cognitive difficulties, and in some cases, headache. Dermatographism can occasionally be associated with autoimmune thyroid conditions.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: Migraines are a type of headache that may bring about severe pain, photo/phonophobia, and in some cases, cognitive disturbances (word-finding difficulty). Muscle pain can also occur as a comorbidity or consequence of the migraine's effect on the body.

diagnoses.name: Infectious diseases (e.g., viral or bacterial infections)
diagnoses.description: Some infections can induce hyperthermia (fever), muscle pain, headaches, and cognitive impairments, including difficulty with word finding. Specific viral infections may also lead to skin manifestations that could be confused with Dermatographism.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. Symptoms can include muscle pain, cognitive issues like word-finding difficulty, and headaches. Dermatographism is not directly related, but skin symptoms can occur due to nerve damage.

diagnoses.name: Drug reactions
diagnoses.description: Certain medications can cause allergic reactions that lead to Dermatographism, hyperthermia, headaches, and muscle pains. Cognitive side effects, including word-finding difficulties, can also emerge with some drugs.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: This complex disorder is characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition. Muscle pain, headaches, and cognitive impairments, including word-finding difficulty, are common symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Heatstroke
diagnoses.description: Heatstroke is a condition caused by your body overheating, usually as a result of prolonged exposure to or physical exertion in high temperatures. It embodies symptoms such as hyperthermia, headache, and muscle pain. Dermatographism and cognitive symptoms could potentially be indirect effects.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. While not directly causing Dermatographism, it can lead to headaches, muscle pain, and word-finding difficulty.

diagnoses.name: COVID-19
diagnoses.description: Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) is a viral respiratory illness that can lead to severe acute respiratory syndrome, hypoxia, and multi-organ dysfunction.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Reaction
diagnoses.description: An exaggerated response of the immune system to a substance that is ordinarily harmless, potentially causing nasal congestion, conjunctival injection, and respiratory distress.

diagnoses.name: Asthma
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory disease of the airways characterized by episodes of wheezing, breathlessness, and chest tightness due to widespread narrowing of the airways.

diagnoses.name: Anaphylaxis
diagnoses.description: A severe, potentially life-threatening allergic reaction that can occur rapidly and affect the body widely, often causing hypoxia, nasal congestion, and abdominal cramps.

diagnoses.name: Pulmonary Embolism
diagnoses.description: A blockage in one of the pulmonary arteries in your lungs, often caused by blood clots that travel to your lungs from your legs or, rarely, other parts of your body (deep vein thrombosis).

diagnoses.name: Heart Failure
diagnoses.description: A chronic condition in which the heart doesn't pump blood as well as it should, leading to fluid buildup and shortness of breath.

diagnoses.name: Viral Pneumonia
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the lung tissue caused by a viral infection, leading to symptoms such as cough, dyspnea, and hypoxia.

diagnoses.name: Influenza
diagnoses.description: A viral infection that attacks your respiratory system — nose, throat, and lungs. Influenza is commonly called the flu, but it's not the same as stomach 'flu' viruses that cause diarrhea and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Sepsis
diagnoses.description: A potentially life-threatening condition caused by the body's response to an infection. Sepsis can lead to tissue damage, organ failure, and death.

diagnoses.name: Acute Sinusitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the sinuses that can lead to nasal congestion, facial pain, and in severe cases, breathing difficulties and systemic symptoms.

A variant of migraine where vertigo is a predominant feature, often accompanied by migraine-type headaches and sensitivity to sound.
Some forms of epilepsy can present with visual disturbances, temporary speech impairments, and other sensory distortions, in addition to seizures.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.details: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms. It's frequently characterized by intense, debilitating headaches.

diagnoses.name: Tension-type headache
diagnoses.details: A common type of headache characterized by a dull, aching pain and tightness in the forehead, neck, or scalp.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.details: A condition in which you lack enough healthy red blood cells to carry adequate oxygen to your body's tissues, causing weakness and fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Hypertension
diagnoses.details: A condition in which the blood pressure in the arteries is persistently elevated, which can lead to headaches and tinnitus.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's disease
diagnoses.details: A disorder of the inner ear that can lead to dizzy spells (vertigo) and hearing loss, in addition to tinnitus and sometimes a feeling of fullness in the ear.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic neuroma
diagnoses.details: A benign tumor on the cranial nerve that connects the inner ear with the brain, leading to hearing loss, tinnitus, and sometimes balance issues.

diagnoses.name: Brain tumor
diagnoses.details: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain; symptoms can vary greatly and may include headaches, weakness, and tinnitus.

diagnoses.name: Multiple sclerosis
diagnoses.details: A disease of the central nervous system that can lead to fatigue, weakness, balance and coordination problems, and sensory issues.

diagnoses.name: Iron deficiency
diagnoses.details: A common cause of anemia, which can lead to symptoms of fatigue, weakness, and headaches.

diagnoses.name: Chronic fatigue syndrome
diagnoses.details: A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition. Headaches and weakness are common symptoms.
